\maketitle

<context prerequisites>
Students should have completed:
- CS 5140 (Introduction to Machine Learning) or equivalent
- MATH 3100 (Linear Algebra)
- STAT 3200 (Probability and Statistics)
- Proficiency in Python and NumPy/PyTorch
</context prerequisites>

<context learning_goals>
By the end of this course, students will be able to:
1. Derive and implement core ML algorithms from scratch.
2. Critically evaluate ML papers and reproduce key results.
3. Design experiments with proper baselines, ablations, and statistical tests.
4. Apply ML methods to real-world datasets with appropriate ethical considerations.
</context learning_goals>

\section{Course Description}

@This course covers advanced topics in machine learning, including deep learning
theory, generative models, reinforcement learning, and fairness in ML. The
course emphasizes both theoretical foundations and practical implementation.@<param context:learning_goals;prerequisites><prompt Rewrite this course description to be more engaging and specific. Mention 2-3 concrete applications students will work on. Mention that this is a research-oriented course where students read and present recent papers. 2 paragraphs.><output This course offers an in-depth exploration of the frontiers of machine learning, spanning deep learning theory, generative models, reinforcement learning, and fairness-aware ML. Rather than surveying these topics at a surface level, students will engage with them through hands-on projects grounded in real-world applications---such as training generative adversarial networks for realistic image synthesis, building a reinforcement learning agent that learns to navigate complex environments, and auditing a classification system for demographic bias. By the end of the semester, you will be able to derive and implement core algorithms from scratch, design rigorous experiments with proper baselines and ablations, and apply ML methods to challenging datasets with appropriate ethical considerations.

This is a \textbf{research-oriented} course: each week, students will read, critically analyze, and present recent papers from top venues such as NeurIPS, ICML, and ICLR. Through structured paper discussions and a semester-long research project, you will develop the skills needed to reproduce key results from the literature, evaluate methodological claims, and ultimately contribute original work to the field. Students are expected to have a solid foundation in machine learning (CS~5140 or equivalent), linear algebra, probability and statistics, and proficiency in Python with NumPy/PyTorch.><hash 6c1342731b0e4fbc>

\section{Prerequisites}

Students must have completed introductory machine learning and linear algebra.
