\section{Grading}

\begin{tabular}{ll}
Homework assignments (4) & 30\% \\
Paper presentations (2) & 15\% \\
Midterm exam & 20\% \\
Final project & 30\% \\
Participation & 5\% \\
\end{tabular}

@The grading breakdown above follows a standard structure but may not
optimally support the learning goals.@<param context:learning_goals><plan Review this grading scheme against the learning goals. Suggest modifications that better incentivize paper reading, reproducibility, and ethical reasoning. Consider whether a midterm exam is the best assessment for a research-oriented graduate course.><output REVISION PLAN: GRADING SCHEME REALIGNMENT

PROBLEM: The midterm exam (20%) tests recall under time pressure, conflicting with research-oriented goals. Paper evaluation (Goal 2), reproducibility (Goal 3), and ethical reasoning (Goal 4) are underweighted. No component explicitly rewards ethical analysis.

RECOMMENDED CHANGES:
- Homework assignments: 30% to 25%
- Paper presentations: 15% (unchanged)
- Midterm exam: 20% to 0% (ELIMINATE)
- NEW Reproducibility study: +10%
- NEW Paper reviews/reading responses: +10%
- NEW Ethics case study: +5%
- Final project: 30% (unchanged)
- Participation: 5% (unchanged)

DETAILS:
1. REPLACE MIDTERM with reproducibility study (10%) and paper reviews (10%). Students select a published result from Weeks 1-6, reproduce it, and write a 3-4 page report documenting methodology, discrepancies, and experimental rigor reflection. Directly exercises Goals 2 and 3.
2. ADD paper review component (10%): 6 written conference-style reviews (1-2 pages each) with summary, strengths, weaknesses, questions. Two designated as "lead reviews" with discussion questions. Builds Goal 2.
3. ADD ethics case study (5%): Students audit a trained model/dataset for fairness issues, write findings, propose mitigations. Tied to Week 12 FAT-ML module. Addresses Goal 4.
4. REDUCE homework from 30% to 25% to accommodate ethics component.
5. RETAIN presentations (15%) and participation (5%).

IMPLEMENTATION: Remove Week 7 midterm from schedule, add reproducibility study deadline. Add paper review template and ethics case study to materials. Add explicit ethical considerations criterion to final project rubric.><hash 059c2adfc36f623f>

\section{Course Schedule}

@\begin{description}
\item[Week 1--2] \textbf{Review of ML Fundamentals.} \\
  \emph{Topics:} Loss functions (cross-entropy, hinge, squared error), $L_1$/$L_2$ regularization, bias-variance tradeoff, gradient descent variants (SGD, Adam, AdaGrad), convergence guarantees, hyperparameter tuning. \\
  \emph{Required Reading:} Bottou, ``Optimization Methods for Large-Scale Machine Learning'' (SIAM Review, 2018); Shalev-Shwartz and Ben-David, \emph{Understanding Machine Learning: From Theory to Algorithms}, Chapters 2--5. \\
  \emph{Assignment:} Problem Set 1 due end of Week 2 --- implement SGD with momentum and Adam from scratch; compare convergence on convex and non-convex objectives.

\item[Week 3--4] \textbf{Deep Learning Theory.} \\
  \emph{Topics:} Universal approximation theorems, depth vs.\ width tradeoffs, Rademacher complexity and generalization bounds for neural networks, double descent, implicit bias of gradient descent, neural tangent kernels, lottery ticket hypothesis. \\
  \emph{Required Reading:} Zhang et al., ``Understanding Deep Learning Requires Rethinking Generalization'' (ICLR 2017); Arora et al., ``Fine-Grained Analysis of Optimization and Generalization for Overparameterized Two-Layer Neural Networks'' (ICML 2019); Frankle and Carlin, ``The Lottery Ticket Hypothesis: Finding Sparse, Trainable Neural Networks'' (ICLR 2019). \\
  \emph{Assignment:} Problem Set 2 due end of Week 4 --- reproduce the memorization experiments from Zhang et al.; analyze generalization gap under varying model capacity and regularization.

\item[Week 5--6] \textbf{Generative Models.} \\
  \emph{Topics:} Variational autoencoders (ELBO derivation, reparameterization trick, posterior collapse), generative adversarial networks (original formulation, Wasserstein GAN, training stability, mode collapse), score-based and diffusion models (denoising score matching, DDPM forward/reverse process, classifier-free guidance). \\
  \emph{Required Reading:} Kingma and Welling, ``Auto-Encoding Variational Bayes'' (ICLR 2014); Goodfellow et al., ``Generative Adversarial Nets'' (NeurIPS 2014); Ho et al., ``Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models'' (NeurIPS 2020); Song et al., ``Score-Based Generative Modeling through Stochastic Differential Equations'' (ICLR 2021). \\
  \emph{Assignment:} Problem Set 3 due end of Week 6 --- implement a VAE and a DDPM on CIFAR-10; compare sample quality using FID scores; perform ablations on noise schedules.

\item[Week 7] \textbf{Midterm Exam.} \\
  \emph{Coverage:} All material from Weeks 1--6. Closed-book, written exam. Emphasis on derivations, theoretical understanding, and experimental design reasoning.

\item[Week 8--9] \textbf{Sequence Models.} \\
  \emph{Topics:} Attention mechanisms (scaled dot-product, multi-head), transformer architecture (encoder-decoder, decoder-only), positional encodings (sinusoidal, rotary, ALiBi), efficient attention (linear attention, flash attention), state-space models (S4, Mamba), long-range dependency benchmarks. \\
  \emph{Required Reading:} Vaswani et al., ``Attention Is All You Need'' (NeurIPS 2017); Gu et al., ``Efficiently Modeling Long Sequences with Structured State Spaces'' (ICLR 2022); Dao et al., ``FlashAttention: Fast and Memory-Efficient Exact Attention with IO-Awareness'' (NeurIPS 2022); Gu and Dao, ``Mamba: Linear-Time Sequence Modeling with Selective State Spaces'' (2023). \\
  \emph{Assignment:} Problem Set 4 due end of Week 9 --- implement a small transformer and an S4 layer from scratch; benchmark on Long Range Arena tasks; analyze attention patterns and computational scaling.

\item[Week 10] \textbf{Self-Supervised Learning.} \\
  \emph{Topics:} Contrastive learning (SimCLR, MoCo), non-contrastive methods (BYOL, Barlow Twins, VICReg), masked image modeling (MAE), masked language modeling (BERT, MLM objective), connections between self-supervised objectives, transfer learning and linear probing evaluation protocols. \\
  \emph{Required Reading:} Chen et al., ``A Simple Framework for Contrastive Learning of Visual Representations'' (ICML 2020); Grill et al., ``Bootstrap Your Own Latent: A New Approach to Self-Supervised Learning'' (NeurIPS 2020); He et al., ``Masked Autoencoders Are Scalable Vision Learners'' (CVPR 2022); Devlin et al., ``BERT: Pre-training of Deep Bidirectional Transformers for Language Understanding'' (NAACL 2019). \\
  \emph{Assignment:} Problem Set 5 due end of Week 10 --- train SimCLR and MAE on a subset of ImageNet; evaluate learned representations via linear probing and $k$-NN classification; compare to supervised baselines.

\item[Week 11--12] \textbf{Reinforcement Learning.} \\
  \emph{Topics:} Markov decision processes, policy gradient methods (REINFORCE, PPO, TRPO), actor-critic architectures, model-based RL (world models, Dreamer), offline RL, RL from human feedback (RLHF), reward modeling. \\
  \emph{Required Reading:} Schulman et al., ``Proximal Policy Optimization Algorithms'' (2017); Hafner et al., ``Dream to Control: Learning Behaviors by Latent Imagination'' (ICLR 2020); Ouyang et al., ``Training Language Models to Follow Instructions with Human Feedback'' (NeurIPS 2022); Levine et al., ``Offline Reinforcement Learning: Tutorial, Review, and Perspectives on Open Problems'' (2020). \\
  \emph{Assignment:} Problem Set 6 due end of Week 12 --- implement REINFORCE and PPO on CartPole and LunarLander environments; compare sample efficiency; design and run ablation studies on hyperparameters with proper statistical reporting (confidence intervals over multiple seeds).

\item[Week 13] \textbf{Fairness, Accountability, and Transparency in ML.} \\
  \emph{Topics:} Sources of bias in ML pipelines, fairness definitions and impossibility results, algorithmic auditing, model interpretability (SHAP, integrated gradients), model cards and datasheets, regulation and governance of AI systems. \\
  \emph{Required Reading:} Mehrabi et al., ``A Survey on Bias and Fairness in Machine Learning'' (ACM Computing Surveys, 2021); Mitchell et al., ``Model Cards for Model Reporting'' (FAT* 2019); Gebru et al., ``Datasheets for Datasets'' (Communications of the ACM, 2021); Chouldechova, ``Fair Prediction with Disparate Impact: A Study of Bias in Recidivism Prediction Instruments'' (Big Data, 2017). \\
  \emph{Assignment:} Ethics case study due end of Week 13 --- audit a pre-trained model for demographic bias on a real-world dataset; produce a model card documenting findings, limitations, and mitigation strategies.

\item[Week 14--15] \textbf{Student Project Presentations.} \\
  \emph{Format:} 20-minute oral presentations followed by 10-minute Q\&A. Projects must include a clearly defined research question, proper baselines, ablation studies, statistical significance tests, and a discussion of ethical implications. \\
  \emph{Deliverables:} Final project report (NeurIPS format, 8 pages + references) and code repository due end of Week 15.
\end{description}@<param output:replace context:learning_goals><prompt Expand each week with specific topics, required readings (use real paper names), and assignment due dates. Add a week on self-supervised learning between sequence models and RL. Format as a LaTeX description list.><hash ed80020bf1d564e1>

\section{Policies}

\subsection{Late Policy}

Each student has <<3 late days>> that may be used across all homework
assignments. After late days are exhausted, a penalty of 10\% per day applies.

\subsection{Academic Integrity}

Students may discuss homework at a high level but must write solutions
independently. Use of large language models (e.g., ChatGPT, Claude) is
permitted for code debugging but not for writing solutions or reports.
@\textbf{Policy on AI and Large Language Model Usage.} This course recognizes that AI tools, including large language models (LLMs) such as ChatGPT, Claude, and GitHub Copilot, are increasingly integral to modern machine learning practice. Rather than prohibiting their use outright, we adopt a policy that encourages responsible engagement while preserving the pedagogical goals of the course.

\medskip
\noindent\textbf{Permitted Uses.} Students may use LLMs and AI-assisted tools for the following purposes:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Clarifying conceptual questions about algorithms, mathematical derivations, or theoretical frameworks covered in lecture.
    \item Debugging code that the student has substantially written themselves.
    \item Generating boilerplate code for data loading, visualization, or standard preprocessing pipelines.
    \item Exploring alternative approaches or brainstorming ideas during the early stages of a project.
    \item Improving the grammar, clarity, or structure of written reports and documentation that the student has drafted.
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textbf{Prohibited Uses.} The following uses of AI tools constitute violations of academic integrity:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Generating complete or near-complete solutions to homework problems, derivations, or proofs.
    \item Using AI tools to produce core algorithmic implementations that are the focus of an assignment (e.g., implementing a neural network architecture from scratch, writing an optimization routine that the assignment is designed to teach).
    \item Submitting AI-generated text as your own written analysis, interpretation, or critical evaluation of results.
    \item Using AI tools during in-class examinations or quizzes unless explicitly authorized.
    \item Using AI to circumvent the learning objectives of any assignment, as stated in its instructions.
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textbf{The Core Principle.} If the primary learning objective of a task is for you to demonstrate understanding of a concept or develop a skill, the intellectual work must be your own. When in doubt, ask the instructor or a TA before submitting.

\medskip
\noindent\textbf{Required Disclosure Format.} All submitted work must include an AI usage declaration. At the end of every assignment, include a section titled \texttt{AI Usage Declaration} containing the following:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Tool(s) Used:} Name and version of each AI tool (e.g., ChatGPT-4, Claude 3.5, GitHub Copilot).
    \item \textbf{Purpose:} A brief description of how each tool was used (e.g., ``Used Claude to debug a dimension mismatch error in my attention mechanism implementation'').
    \item \textbf{Extent:} An honest characterization of the scope---whether the tool provided a minor suggestion, helped restructure an approach, or generated substantive content that was then adapted.
    \item \textbf{Modification:} A description of how you modified, verified, or built upon any AI-generated output.
\end{enumerate}
If no AI tools were used, include the statement: ``No AI tools were used in the preparation of this submission.''

\medskip
\noindent\textbf{Documenting AI-Assisted Code.} Any code that incorporates AI-generated content must be documented as follows:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Include an inline comment marking the beginning and end of any AI-assisted block, using the format:\\ \texttt{\% --- AI-assisted (tool: [name], purpose: [brief description]) ---}\\ and \texttt{\% --- End AI-assisted ---}
    \item In your accompanying report or notebook, explain in your own words what the AI-assisted code does and why it is correct.
    \item AI-generated code that you do not understand and cannot explain will be treated as unauthorized collaboration, regardless of whether it produces correct output.
\end{itemize}

\medskip
\noindent\textbf{Consequences for Violations.} Violations of this policy will be handled in accordance with the university's academic integrity procedures and may include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textit{First offense (minor):} A zero on the affected assignment and a required meeting with the instructor to discuss proper AI usage practices.
    \item \textit{First offense (major) or second offense:} A failing grade in the course and referral to the Office of Academic Integrity.
    \item \textit{Failure to disclose:} Undisclosed AI usage, even for otherwise permitted purposes, will be treated as a violation. Transparent disclosure will always be viewed more favorably than concealment.
\end{itemize}

\noindent The distinction between minor and major offenses is at the discretion of the instructor, based on the scope of the violation and its impact on the learning objectives of the assignment. Students may appeal any determination through the university's standard academic integrity appeals process.@<param output:replace><prompt Expand this into a nuanced AI-usage policy for a graduate ML course. Address: when LLM use is acceptable vs. not, required disclosure format, how AI-assisted code should be documented, and consequences for violations. Balance encouraging responsible AI use with maintaining academic rigor.><hash 90df2ecb61f27f09>

